        <h3>I don't know what element to put in here but here is an horror story.</h3>
        <br />
        <p>The rain had not stopped for three days when Arman finally returned to his grandmother’s house. The wooden structure stood at the edge of a narrow road, surrounded by trees that seemed to lean closer than he remembered. He had avoided this place for years, ever since her funeral. Yet now, with nowhere else to go, he pushed open the swollen door. It creaked in a way that felt less like sound and more like a warning.</p>
        <br />
        <p>Inside, the air was thick and unmoving. Dust clung to every surface, but something felt off. The floorboards near the hallway looked recently disturbed, as if someone had been pacing there. Arman paused, listening. At first, there was nothing but the distant hum of rain. Then, faintly, he heard it. Footsteps. Slow. Measured. Coming from the back of the house.</p>
        <br />
        <p>He told himself it was just water dripping or wood shifting. Still, he followed the sound, each step heavier than the last. The hallway seemed longer than it should be, stretching unnaturally. The door to his grandmother’s room was slightly open. He didn’t remember leaving it that way. As he pushed it open, the footsteps stopped.</p>
        <br />
        <p>The room was exactly as it had been years ago. The bed neatly made, the curtains drawn, the faint scent of old perfume lingering. But in the corner stood a figure. Thin. Motionless. Facing the wall. Arman’s throat tightened as he whispered, “Hello?” The figure slowly tilted its head, but not its body, until it faced him. Its face was wrong. Not empty, not decayed—just… incorrect, like something trying to imitate a human expression and failing.</p>
        <br />
        <p>Before he could move, it spoke in a voice that layered over itself, as if multiple people were speaking at once. “You weren’t supposed to come back.” The door behind him slammed shut. The lights flickered once, then died. In the darkness, the footsteps resumed—but this time, they were right behind him.</p>
